Recommendations
3.12	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
3.12.1	Create an appraisal / inventory committee to prepare an inventory plan and to conduct an actual physical inventory taking of all property, plant and equipment headed by the General Service Officer and witnessed by any representative of the Commission on Audit;
3.12.2	Require the General Service Officer to regularly maintain property cards for each property, plant and equipment and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
3.12.3	Direct the Municipal Accountant to update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
3.12.4	Direct the concerned personnel to conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
3.12.5	Augment the number of personnel assigned under the General Service Office and Municipal Accountant Office to fasten the process of inventory plan and reconciliation of accounts.

Recommendations:
We recommended that Management undertake the following:
Require the Municipal Assessors Office to:
Adopt and implement the guidelines and procedures in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in the physical count of PPE for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies for the proper disposal of unserviceable properties; and
Prepare a summary of asset classifications of the items found during the physical count and submit the same together with the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to ensure a smooth reconciliation process with the accounting;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and periodically update the schedule of items composing the PPE accounts, together with pertinent data such as the acquisition cost, acquisition date and estimated useful life. After which, apply the guidelines prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022 relative to the increase of capitalization threshold for PPE;
Prepare a lapsing schedule and provide depreciation to PPE accounts and constantly review and monitor the PPE Lapsing Schedule and evaluate the correctness of the data using the underlying provisions and basis of computation in IPSAS 17, other generally accepted accounting principles, and COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Undertake regular reconciliation of accounting and GSO records and promptly adjust any discrepancies noted to ensure complete and reliable PPE account balances at any given reporting period.

a. Create an appraisal / inventory committee to prepare an inventory plan and to conduct an actual physical inventory taking of all property, plant and equipment headed by the General Service Officer and witnessed by any representative of the Commission on Audit;

b. Require the General Service Officer to regularly maintain property cards for each property, plant and equipment and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);

c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);

d. Direct the concerned personnel to conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

e. Augment the number of personnel assigned under the General Service Office and Municipal Accountant Office to fasten the process of inventory plan and reconciliation of accounts.

We recommended that the Sangguniang Bayan as a legislative body, stop discharging the duties of the Local Chief Executive who under Article 87 of the Implementing Rules and Regulations of the Republic Act. No.7160, has been given the sole power to exercise control over all programs, projects, services, and activities of the municipality.

Moreover, we recommended that officials:

a.	Stop charging against public fund religious and personal expenses;

b.	To eliminate double claims and for proper documentation, consolidate in one Office-the Municipal Social Welfare and Development (MSWD)- the grant of financial assistance to persons in crisis situations and for MSWD to formulate guidelines which shall include:

1. documents authenticating the identity of claimant, and relationship if the claimant is not the person sought to be assisted;
2. documents that will identify the requesters as individuals under crisis situation;
3. relevant documents that would attest the claim; and   
4. 	maximum financial assistance for each type assistance.

Submit documents required under COA Circular No. 2007-001 for the grant of funds to non-government/people’s organizations, should they qualify;

 Require both government and non-government entities to submit liquidation report of financial assistance granted them; and
Adhere to the provision of COA Circular no. 2007-001 in the grant, utilization and accounting of funds released to non-government/people’s organizations; and 
Ensure that financial assistance is received by the requester.

