We therefore recommended that BAC:

1.	Stop committing the errors noted in the attached matrix (Appendix A-10) and henceforth, strictly follow the prescribed general processes in the procurement of supplies and other similar transactions;

2.	Procure drugs and medicines through competitive public bidding, unless the conditions to resort to alternative modes of procurement be justified and met, to avail the most advantageous prices of the goods to be procured.

We recommended that Management:
Allow only duly bonded officers to collect money for the government or apply proper bonding of additional designated collecting officers pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009;
Increase the fidelity bond of accountable officers whose collections require a greater accountability;
Require accountable officers to remit their collections daily to the Municipal Treasurer and record their collections daily in the Cashbook;
Enjoin the Municipal Treasurer to deposit collections/remittances with authorized government depository bank/s daily or not later than the next banking day; and 
Conform to the prescribed procedures under COA Circular No. 92-382 dated July 3, 1992 in the recording, turnover and deposit of collections and remittances.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

1. Direct the Human Resource Officer to compute the money value of earned leave credits of the LGU personnel;

2. Direct the Human Resource Officer to furnish copies to the Municipal Accountant Designate for recording purposes;

3. Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to review properly the earned leave credits before recording in the book of accounts; and

4. Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to provide allocation especially to employees nearing retirement, otherwise the Municipal Accountant Designate may disclose it in the Notes to Financial Statements for information purposes.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to prepare and submit the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements in adherence to Section 74 of PD 1445 and COA Circular No. 96-11. Also require her to get the monthly bank statements from the depository bank promptly and regularly;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile his cashbooks entries with that from the accounting records at least quarterly;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to enroll the bank accounts to on-line e-access in the Land Bank of the Philippines/Development Bank of the Philippines/Philippine National Bank and grant access to the Municipal Accountant in order that she can view immediately the balances on line and can possibly print the balances of accounts of the LGU.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to record and transfer the Local Road Networks from the Public Infrastructure Registry to the books of accounts in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Direct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant Designate to revisit the map of the municipality’s local road networks and determine the proper cost for each local road through thorough review of records;
Direct the General Services Officer/Municipal Treasurer to conduct Inventory of Roads.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the General Services Officer (GSO) / Municipal Treasurer to conduct Inventory;
Create an appraisal / inventory committee to conduct actual physical inventory taking of all properties, plant and equipment;
Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to:
Make necessary adjustments on the records for deficiencies noted in the course of inventory taking and in the reconciliation of the inventory report with the subsidiary ledgers;
After physical count and report of PPE’s are completed, prepare and maintain a subsidiary ledger card on each equipment and should bear a Property Number; and
Provide residual value in computing the depreciation.
Direct the Administrative Officer to update the list of properties that needs to be insured and submit the same to GSIS. This will guarantee that all properties are adequately covered by insurance in order to protect the interest of the government. For lost / damaged properties without covering insurance, liability therefore should devolve upon the parties responsible.

